  <H2>Effect of Frequency Distribution</H2>

  <Body>The shape of the frequency distribution g(ω) significantly affects the synchronization behavior:</Body>

  <Body>• Width: Broader distributions (larger γ or σ) require stronger coupling to synchronize. This is intuitive—more heterogeneous populations are harder to synchronize.</Body>

  <Body>• Shape: The Lorentzian distribution has heavy tails, meaning some oscillators have frequencies very far from the mean. The Gaussian distribution has lighter tails. Interestingly, for the Gaussian case, K_c = √(8/π)σ ≈ 1.60σ.</Body>

  <Body>• Peak height: The critical coupling is inversely proportional to g(0), the height of the distribution at its center. A sharper peak means more oscillators near the mean frequency, making synchronization easier.</Body>

