  <H2>Biological Applications: Brain Rhythms</H2>

  <Body>The Kuramoto model provides a powerful framework for understanding neural synchronization phenomena:</Body>

  <H3>Alpha Rhythm (8-13 Hz)</H3>
  <Body>The posterior alpha rhythm, prominent during relaxed wakefulness with eyes closed, emerges from synchronized activity in thalamocortical circuits. The Kuramoto model explains how this coherent oscillation can emerge from populations of neurons with heterogeneous intrinsic frequencies. The "alpha blocking" phenomenon—where alpha power decreases upon eye opening—can be modeled as a decrease in effective coupling strength K below the critical value.</Body>

  <H3>Epileptic Seizures</H3>
  <Body>Epileptic seizures are characterized by pathologically strong synchronization across large neuronal populations. In the Kuramoto framework, seizure onset can be viewed as a transition from a partially synchronized or incoherent state to a highly synchronized state (r → 1). This can occur through:</Body>
  <Body>• Increased coupling K (e.g., due to enhanced excitatory connections or reduced inhibition)</Body>
  <Body>• Decreased frequency heterogeneity (narrower g(ω))</Body>
  <Body>• Both mechanisms acting together</Body>

  <Body>This perspective suggests therapeutic strategies: anticonvulsant drugs that reduce coupling or increase heterogeneity would raise K_c, making the synchronized seizure state harder to reach.</Body>

  <H3>Gamma Oscillations and Cognition</H3>
  <Body>Gamma rhythms (30-100 Hz) are associated with cognitive processing, attention, and working memory. Fast-spiking inhibitory interneurons play a key role in generating gamma through mutual inhibition, which can be modeled using Kuramoto-like frameworks with modifications for inhibitory coupling. The emergence and dissolution of gamma synchronization during cognitive tasks reflects dynamic changes in effective coupling strength.</Body>

  <FlashCard id="fc-seizure-kuramoto">
