  <H2>Extensions and Limitations</H2>

  <Body>The basic Kuramoto model has inspired numerous extensions that address its limitations:</Body>

  <Body>• Delay coupling: Real neural connections have propagation delays, modifying the coupling to sin(θ_j(t-τ) - θ_i(t)). This can lead to multistability and complex dynamics.</Body>

  <Body>• Network topology: The all-to-all coupling assumption rarely holds in real neural circuits. Network Kuramoto models on graphs with specific topologies (small-world, scale-free) reveal how structure affects synchronization.</Body>

  <Body>• Higher harmonics: The sinusoidal coupling is a first-order approximation. Including higher harmonics sin(n(θ_j - θ_i)) captures more complex phase interactions.</Body>

  <Body>• Noise: Adding Gaussian white noise ξ_i(t) to the equations models thermal fluctuations or synaptic noise, leading to stochastic Kuramoto models.</Body>

  <Body>• Adaptive coupling: The coupling strength K can evolve based on the system's state, modeling plasticity-like mechanisms.</Body>

