  <H2>Summary</H2>

  <Body>The Kuramoto model elegantly captures the essence of collective synchronization in coupled oscillator systems. Key takeaways include:</Body>

  <Body>1. The model describes N phase oscillators coupled through sinusoidal interactions, with natural frequencies drawn from a distribution g(ω).</Body>

  <Body>2. The order parameter r ∈ [0, 1] quantifies coherence, transitioning from r = 0 (incoherent) to r &gt; 0 (synchronized) as coupling K increases past the critical value K_c.</Body>

  <Body>3. Mean-field theory provides exact results in the thermodynamic limit, including K_c = 2/(πg(0)) for unimodal symmetric distributions.</Body>

  <Body>4. The synchronization transition is a continuous phase transition analogous to the ferromagnetic transition, with r growing as √(K - K_c) near K_c.</Body>

  <Body>5. The model provides insights into brain rhythms, including normal oscillations (alpha, gamma) and pathological states (epileptic seizures).</Body>

